# Error Handling

## Error Boundaries

Wrap major sections and lazy-loaded routes. The ONE exception where class components are allowed.

```tsx
export class ErrorBoundary extends Component<ErrorBoundaryProps, ErrorBoundaryState> {
  state: ErrorBoundaryState = { hasError: false };
  static getDerivedStateFromError(): ErrorBoundaryState { return { hasError: true }; }
  componentDidCatch(error: Error, info: ErrorInfo) { /* log to monitoring — never console.log */ }
  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) return this.props.fallback ?? <ErrorFallback />;
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

## Fallback Patterns

- Lazy chunks: `<ErrorBoundary>` wrapping `<Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>`
- Images: `onError` swaps to placeholder. Never broken image icons.
- API/submissions: inline errors at point of failure, `LoadingState` enum (IDLE → LOADING → SUCCESS | ERROR)
- Network errors: show retry option

## Rules

- Never let an unhandled error crash the full page.
- Never show raw errors or stack traces to users.
- Every async operation handles its error case.
- Error fallback UIs styled consistently, translated via i18n.

